natural problem: What is the value of the expression $x^2+ 5x-6$, when $x =-1$?

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real and P :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. P x = x powr 2 + 5 * x - 6"
and h1 : "x = -1"
shows  "P x = -10"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 What is the value of the expression $x^2+ 5x-6$, when $x =-1$? The final Answer is -10
 ### Proof
 \[ x^2+5x-6=(-1)^2+5(-1)-6=1-5-6=\boxed{-10}. \]
 *)

fixes x :: real and P :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"

 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
